  "value": "Medium",
  "why": "The paper provides partial diagnostic insight: it analyzes statistical patterns of failures (counts by SUT, by mutation type, severity over time) and inspects concrete input-level causes (examples showing occlusion, perspective, lighting issues and a manual false-positive analysis). However, it does not link failures to underlying model vulnerabilities (e.g., reliance on spurious/non-robust features, dataset bias) nor analyze model internals (neuron activations, coverage, etc.) or propose specific root-cause remediations. Thus the work goes beyond merely reporting failures but stops short of causal explanations tied to model weaknesses.",
  "evidence": "Section 6.4.1 (RQ1 Results) — statistical failure patterns: \"1210 SUT inconsistencies resulting from 884 mutations and that each SUT had over 100 inconsistencies.\" and \"The distribution of inconsistencies among the SUTs is unexpected. NVIDIA SemSeg [34] and EfficientPS [24], the two highest scoring on the Cityscapes benchmark, had the highest number of inconsistencies in all three categories with 211 and 477 respectively.\" (pp. 1966, Section 6.4.1). Section 6.4.3 (RQ3 Results) — mutation-level diagnosis: \"The add car mutation induced the most inconsistencies (877), followed by the add person mutation (280), and then the mutation to change the car color (53)... we find that the SUTs are robust against changing the color of the car.\" (pp. 1967, Section 6.4.3). Concrete input-level examples and manual inspection: \"The leftmost column shows a moderate inconsistency; an added person occludes a bus, causing EfficientPS to then classify the bus as a train.\" and \"we manually inspect all the generated test cases that led to 5+ p.p. drop... The process entailed each author examining each image and classifying them as either a true positive or false positive.\" (pp. 1966, Section 6.4.1; Fig. 12 & Fig. 14). Analysis of common input causes/nonconformities: \"Figure 9a shows an example of a car that has been added to an image with a perspective mismatch... another issue related to entity placement is overlap... inconsistent lighting... missing shadow.\" (pp. 1963, Section 4.3.2). Use of output-level metric only (no internals): \"we rely on the Cityscapes benchmark evaluation tool (eval) which scores each SUT’s performance based on the percentage of correctly classified pixels... the drop is given by drop = eval(Percep(r), interp) - eval(Percep(r'), interp')\" (pp. 1965, Section 6.3). No discussion or results analyzing model internals (activations, feature reliance, coverage) or tying failures to specific model vulnerabilities is provided in the paper."
